      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7a0e24e7eb1aaccc",
      "text": "The assertion that feelings function according to the principle of bivalent logic may seem strange at first glance. After all, everyone has probably experienced ambivalence and felt torn between the desire for closeness and distance, love and hate, autonomy and the desire for attachment.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "80b1c73fe5d5399a",
      "text": "However, such an experience can only come about because thinking and feeling do not function in isolation from each other, even if they are experienced differently. They comment on each other. With the help of logical-discursive thinking, stable units, e.g. persons or social systems (such as nations etc.), are constructed in the description of self and others. A number of characteristics are ascribed to them, which constitute their constant identity over time."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1425b4de56571543",
      "text": "If an observer (who does not have to be a person, but can also be an observing system) can be present at two events, then he constructs space; if he cannot be present and learns about it, he constructs time. In both cases he must be able to distinguish between two events and know about both. He can acquire this knowledge if he is either present at both events or if he learns about them through communication with others. If he is present at both, then he must perceive both as spatially separate (and thus construct the space), otherwise he would perceive them as a unit and would only be dealing with one event. In connection with the simultaneity of their perception, their localization in space takes place (one event is more up/down, front/back, right/left than the other) and so on. ..."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9edb98c97488306b",
      "text": "If the observer cannot or is not present at both events, then he must receive some news of them (for example, someone tells about them, a newspaper reports, an astronomer registers radio waves from a long-extinct star). In this case, time is constructed; distinguishable events can only take place at the same place at different times."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2283fb04ae37be40",
      "text": "In order to attribute an identity to itself, an observing system must develop memory. In self-observation, it must define itself as distinct from the rest of the world and keep this definition or the characteristics of the distinction stable and constant. It must locate events in which it is present on the one hand on the inside (\"I\", \"we\", the \"system\") and on the other hand on the outside (\"you\", \"they\", the \"environment\") within the meaning of the inside-outside distinction. Such a system-environment distinction implies the construction of space. Events in which the system is not present, but in which it was present and which it still remembers or in which it will presumably or hopefully be present, require the temporalization of the self-description."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "736be426d9e799cc",
      "text": "In order to be able to describe oneself as constant and identical with oneself over time, it is necessary to reproduce certain events (experiences, actions, communications), and it is necessary to reproduce the distinction between inside and outside, i.e. the constantly active demarcation from the respective environments."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "67630ef64b19b272",
      "text": "In relation to the human individual as an observer, it can be stated that logical-discursive thinking and feeling have different functions in the construction of world views."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "50c62fdc60162ba6",
      "text": "Logical-discursive thinking ensures fine-grained distinctions, differentiation, complex interrelationships and the construction of stories. Events inside and outside the organism are perceived \"diacritically\" with the help of different sensory organs and organized spatially and temporally. They can be experienced simultaneously, combined with each other and organized into different patterns. The resulting world view is complex and differentiated."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a49e50b6947c648",
      "text": "In contrast, feelings function \"coaesthetically\" throughout the body according to the all-or-nothing or either-or principle. You either have a feeling or you don't. And if you experience it, then you experience it completely or not at all. There is no third party. Since you only ever feel in the present, feelings have no time. The feelings of then, yesterday, just now are already in the past. They are events that pass quickly and therefore have to be reproduced again and again if they are to stand the test of time. Or rather, they do not outlast time, but are only identified with each other in the observation of their reproduction. You don't get into the same feeling twice. Only in (self-)observation does the feeling of yesterday become the \"same\" feeling as today. Due to their eventfulness, feelings can also change and oscillate very quickly, so that they can be individually experienced and assigned as almost simultaneous."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bc2d92a0bda33ab6",
      "text": "Diacritical sensory perception is organized in a more differentiated way, and it is only with its help in self-observation that the feelings of yesterday can be compared with those of today. Current experience is linked to logical (or illogical) constructions of reality, with the help of which individuals reduce the complexity of the world, describe it, explain it and ultimately evaluate it affectively."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b3366c15a5fc06b4",
      "text": "How such affect-logical schemata are structured in the warrior (whereby this martial term refers neither to a profession nor a personality structure, but to a describable psychological state, a form in which thinking and feeling are coordinated) has already been described in detail above. This form of [[Psychodynamics]] can be explained as the result of the \"[[Synchronization]]\" of thinking and feeling. Both are no longer different in their degree of differentiation (thinking fine-grained, feeling coarse-grained), but the structures of thinking adapt to those of feeling. The all-or-nothing pattern of our emotional life organizes the selection of perceived events as well as their explanation and evaluation as an \"ordering parameter\". This leads to a reduction of complexity, a de-differentiation and coarsening of the criteria for differentiation, right down to simple, binary schemes: friend or foe, us and the others, etc. Contradictions and inconsistencies are rendered invisible, as they fall out of the \"coarse-grained\" differentiation schemes. And since they are almost always linked to the good/evil distinction, they are usually valorized or devalued, idealized positively or negatively. Predominantly \"gods\" and \"heroes\" or \"Satan\" and the \"forces of darkness\" are constructed; good is at war with the forces of evil. Intermediate tones can no longer be heard, ambiguity and undecidability are eliminated. All of this seems inadequate for describing and evaluating real living beings in all their mediocrity and contradictions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3dacc94341130c97",
      "text": "There is also a change in the sense of time, the present alone counts. The focus of attention is narrowed in terms of time. The future is ignored or seen in an undifferentiated way as the time to come when everything will be fine. This corresponds to the nature of feeling, which is always only related to the present. Finally, if the past and future no longer play a role in thinking, then one of its essential qualities – temporal perspectivity – is not utilized."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "eef4ca7b6f347fb4",
      "text": "These are all cognitive aspects that can (i.e. do not have to) be useful under the decision-making pressure of emergency situations, but which are almost always dysfunctional in the long term if they become chronic. Although they can be used to make quick decisions, they make it very unlikely that the costs and benefits of alternative decision-making options will be carefully weighed up."
