      "type": "edit",
      "id": "b3366c15a5fc06b4",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b3366c15a5fc06b4",
        "text": "How such affect-logical schemata are structured in the warrior (whereby this martial term refers neither to a profession nor a personality structure, but to a describable psychological state, a form in which thinking and feeling are coordinated) has already been described in detail above. This form of psychodynamics can be explained as the result of the \"synchronization\" of thinking and feeling. Both are no longer different in their degree of differentiation (thinking fine-grained, feeling coarse-grained), but the structures of thinking adapt to those of feeling. The all-or-nothing pattern of our emotional life organizes the selection of perceived events as well as their explanation and evaluation as an \"ordering parameter\". This leads to a reduction of complexity, a de-differentiation and coarsening of the criteria for differentiation, right down to simple, binary schemes: friend or foe, us and the others, etc. Contradictions and inconsistencies are rendered invisible, as they fall out of the \"coarse-grained\" differentiation schemes. And since they are almost always linked to the good/evil distinction, they are usually valorized or devalued, idealized positively or negatively. Predominantly \"gods\" and \"heroes\" or \"Satan\" and the \"forces of darkness\" are constructed; good is at war with the forces of evil. Intermediate tones can no longer be heard, ambiguity and undecidability are eliminated. All of this seems inadequate for describing and evaluating real living beings in all their mediocrity and contradictions.\""
